𝐒𝐨𝐮𝐧𝐝𝐬 𝐨𝐟 𝐭𝐡𝐞 𝟖𝟎𝐬: 𝐀 𝐉𝐨𝐮𝐫𝐧𝐞𝐲 𝐁𝐚𝐜𝐤 𝐢𝐧 𝐓𝐢𝐦𝐞 

The 1980s was a decade full of unforgettable moments, and the sounds of that time were just as iconic. These nostalgic memories transport us to a simpler yet exciting era:

 The satisfying click and whir of rewinding a cassette tape.
️ The sharp ring of a rotary phone, signaling important conversations.
 The mechanical grind of a floppy disk drive loading up important files.
️ The cheerful beep-boop of arcade games that sparked hours of fun.
 The nostalgic static hiss of a TV antenna being adjusted for the perfect signal.

Each sound brings back memories of innovation, fun, and discovery. From music and gaming to early tech, the 80s shaped much of what we cherish today.

Which iconic sound from the past sparks nostalgia for you, even if you didn’t experience it firsthand? Let’s relive the magic together in the comments! 

 Follow me for more nostalgic moments and timeless stories!

posts.name:
Steve Litzow
Steve Litzow
posts.content:
Big deal about to close... but it’s not the ICP?

When I work on refining sales strategies for scale ups, I always include a validation step.

It comes after the proposal and negotiation.

It’s an internal step for:
– The CEO or VP of Sales to review the deal.
– The SDR or sales manager to self-analyze.
– An item to discuss during weekly or monthly deal reviews.

The key focus of validation?

Double-check the customer still fits your ICP.

It’s overlooked because:
– The SDR wants to hit quota.
– The sales manager wants to hit quota.
– Or simply, the revenue is too tempting to resist.

But if you’re serious about scaling to 8 or 9 figures, you must take this step.

You must reconsider going ahead if the ICP isn’t the right fit.

Here’s why…

I recently read a story from Jake Fuentes, co-founder of Cascade, about why he shut his startup down.

He admitted that “ICP fray” was a key factor.

Cascade initially defined their ICP as “nontechnical business analysts using Excel to crunch big data sets”.

The definition was too broad.

They ended up chasing customers with wildly different use cases:
– A scooter company managing location data.
– An HR team managing employee data.

They didn’t have a framework to accept or reject opportunities, so they tried to support them all.

Jake described this as “a slow death of a thousand cuts.”

Supporting anyone and everyone pulled the company in a million directions, ultimately diluting their focus and stunting growth.

If you want to scale successfully, rejecting deals from prospects who don’t fit your ICP is the tough but necessary way forward.

Validate every deal.

Stick to your guns.

Keep closing.

posts.name:
Shail Khiyara
Shail Khiyara
posts.content:
𝗧𝗵𝗲 𝗟𝗲𝗮𝗱𝗲𝗿𝘀𝗵𝗶𝗽 𝗦𝗲𝗰𝗿𝗲𝘁 𝘁𝗼 𝗗𝗿𝗶𝘃𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗚𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘁𝗵: 𝟱 𝗠𝗶𝗻𝗱𝘀𝗲𝘁𝘀 𝗧𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗠𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿

In a world where growth is often seen as a function of market conditions or sheer luck, the truth is far more actionable: 𝗚𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘁𝗵 𝗶𝘀 𝗮 𝗰𝗵𝗼𝗶𝗰𝗲.

's 5 key mindsets that separate growth-driven leaders from aspirational ones, really resonated with me.

1️⃣ 𝗣𝗿𝗶𝗼𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗶𝘇𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗚𝗿𝗼𝘄𝘁𝗵: Great leaders place growth at the heart of their strategy—not as a byproduct, but as a deliberate priority.

2️⃣ 𝗔𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗕𝗼𝗹𝗱𝗹𝘆: They embrace calculated risks and make courageous decisions. Playing it safe rarely drives transformative results.

3️⃣ 𝗖𝘂𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗺𝗲𝗿-𝗖𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗰𝗶𝘁𝘆: These leaders deeply understand their customers, innovating and delivering value that meets real needs.

4️⃣ 𝗔𝘁𝘁𝗿𝗮𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗡𝘂𝗿𝘁𝘂𝗿𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗧𝗮𝗹𝗲𝗻𝘁: Growth is a team sport. Building and empowering the right people is non-negotiable.

5️⃣ 𝗘𝘅𝗲𝗰𝘂𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝘄𝗶𝘁𝗵 𝗥𝗶𝗴𝗼𝗿: Ideas are easy; execution is everything. Discipline in execution sets growth leaders apart.

This framework isn’t just theoretical—it’s actionable. In my experience, these mindsets serve as a roadmap for leaders in any industry, whether you're scaling a startup, driving innovation through AI and automation, or navigating transformation in a legacy enterprise.

𝗪𝗵𝘆 𝗧𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗠𝗮𝘁𝘁𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗡𝗼𝘄

In a time where 𝘂𝗻𝗰𝗲𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝘆 𝗶𝘀 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗼𝗻𝗹𝘆 𝗰𝗲𝗿𝘁𝗮𝗶𝗻𝘁𝘆, 𝗹𝗲𝗮𝗱𝗲𝗿𝘀 𝗻𝗲𝗲𝗱 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗮𝗻 𝗮𝗺𝗯𝗶𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻; 𝘁𝗵𝗲𝘆 𝗻𝗲𝗲𝗱 𝗮 𝘀𝘆𝘀𝘁𝗲𝗺. Growth doesn’t just happen—it’s the outcome of 𝗱𝗲𝗹𝗶𝗯𝗲𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗲 𝗳𝗼𝗰𝘂𝘀, 𝗯𝗼𝗹𝗱 𝗱𝗲𝗰𝗶𝘀𝗶𝗼𝗻𝘀, 𝗮𝗻𝗱 𝗱𝗶𝘀𝗰𝗶𝗽𝗹𝗶𝗻𝗲𝗱 𝗮𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻.

Consider this: Companies that actively 𝗽𝗿𝗶𝗼𝗿𝗶𝘁𝗶𝘇𝗲 𝗰𝘂𝘀𝘁𝗼𝗺𝗲𝗿-𝗰𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗿𝗶𝗰 𝘀𝘁𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗲𝗴𝗶𝗲𝘀 𝗮𝗿𝗲 𝟲𝟬% 𝗺𝗼𝗿𝗲 𝗽𝗿𝗼𝗳𝗶𝘁𝗮𝗯𝗹𝗲 than those that don’t. This is not just about theory—it’s a proven driver of results.

Ask yourself: Do your growth priorities align with customer needs? Are you empowering your team with the tools, skills, and autonomy to excel?

𝗖𝗮𝗹𝗹 𝘁𝗼 𝗔𝗰𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗻:

If you’re a leader (or aspire to be one), take a moment to reflect:

Which of these mindsets are already strong for you?
Which need more focus in 2025?

comments.commentText: If you just had to focus on ONE of these mindsets, which one would it be and why?

Shail, your insights on leadership and growth are truly inspiring. Emphasizing these mindsets as actionable steps is a game changer for anyone looking to drive meaningful results. Thank you for sharing such valuable perspectives.

There's zero risk in cold calling a prospect.

The worst that can happen

• You talk to the wrong person
→ 1 step closer to the right one

• You get some objections
→ opportunity for discovery

• You get hung up on
→ whoops, it can happen

• You get yelled at
→ fire these prospects

Whatever happens, it's better than bumping your email with "thoughts?" for the 11th time.

I hope this will take away some people's fears around cold calling.

Just get comfortable with the uncomfortable.

Trust me: you'll book more meetings faster.

posts.content:
It takes commitment to build a business, it takes 10x MORE to build a community ↴

Hear me out.

Building a business is NOT the same as building a community. They both require a different focus and perspective.

I know some fantastic entrepreneurs who are also building amazing communities.

But they are not the same thing.


Building a business is:

- for you
- revenue focussed
- team centred


Building a community is:

- for them
- ‘feeling’ focussed
- relationship centred


Frankly, in this day and age the fastest way to grow your business is to build a community. And this is where some people get a little confused.

STOP selling, START sharing.

In other words, build a community that loves you and the rest will follow. This requires commitment to others. It requires you to be selfless. It requires you to sometimes put someone else before your own goals for a change.

THIS is what community really means.

And it’s also what distinguishes a good personal brand, from a GREAT one.

So get building.

(This is something I’m going to be able to help you with very soon )


What are your best tips for building a strong community? Let me know in the comments!


P.S on that note, I’m forever grateful for this growing community on LinkedIn (over 20k of you now!) If you want to join in, give mea follow for more on personal branding, PR and how to really stand out.

And repost this if it resonated.️
